TUnit uses `[Before(…)]` / `[After(…)]` attributes with a `HookType` enum to control scope. Here's a sketch for each:

## 1. Before/After Every Test (method-level)

```csharp
public class MyTests
{
    [Before(Test)]
    public void ResetDatabase()
    {
        InMemoryDb.Reset();
    }

    [After(Test)]
    public void Cleanup()
    {
        InMemoryDb.Clear();
    }

    [Test]
    public void SomeTest() { /* ... */ }
}
```

## 2. Once Per Class (class-level)

```csharp
public class MyTests
{
    private static HttpClient _client;

    [Before(Class)]
    public static void OpenFixture()
    {
        _client = new HttpClient();
    }

    [After(Class)]
    public static void DisposeFixture()
    {
        _client.Dispose();
    }

    [Test]
    public void SomeTest() { /* ... */ }
}
```

Note: class-level hooks must be **static**.

## 3. Once Per Assembly

```csharp
public class GlobalSetup
{
    [Before(Assembly)]
    public static void StartWireMock()
    {
        WireMockServer.Start();
    }

    [After(Assembly)]
    public static void StopWireMock()
    {
        WireMockServer.Stop();
    }
}
```

The class can live anywhere in the assembly — TUnit discovers it by the attribute.

## 4. Once Per Entire Test Session (cross-assembly)

```csharp
public class SessionSetup
{
    [Before(TestSession)]
    public static void ApplyMigrations()
    {
        Database.Migrate();
    }

    [After(TestSession)]
    public static void TearDown()
    {
        Database.Drop();
    }
}
```

`TestSession` spans all assemblies in the run.

---

### Summary table

| Scope | Attribute | Must be static? |
|-------|-----------|-----------------|
| Each test | `[Before(Test)]` / `[After(Test)]` | No |
| Class | `[Before(Class)]` / `[After(Class)]` | Yes |
| Assembly | `[Before(Assembly)]` / `[After(Assembly)]` | Yes |
| Session | `[Before(TestSession)]` / `[After(TestSession)]` | Yes |

All hooks support `async Task` return types as well. The enum values come from `TUnit.Core.HookType`.
